WEBVTT

00:00.260 --> 00:01.780
- [Gordon] Tonight on Hotel Hell,

00:01.780 --> 00:02.649
(siren blaring)

00:02.649 --> 00:06.204
a near-fatal accident has
left Mississippi hotel owners

00:06.204 --> 00:07.820
in a desperate situation.

00:07.820 --> 00:10.072
- Legs.
- I broke both of my ankles

00:10.072 --> 00:12.741
and back in two places.

00:12.741 --> 00:14.358
- The business is failing.

00:14.358 --> 00:16.036
And with not enough money coming in,

00:16.036 --> 00:18.309
this married couple have lost their home.

00:18.309 --> 00:19.853
You live in here?
- Yes.

00:19.853 --> 00:20.787
- [Gordon] There's not even a window!

00:20.787 --> 00:22.209
- You have to do what you have to do!

00:22.209 --> 00:23.575
- [Gordon] If I don't do something soon,

00:23.575 --> 00:24.955
they will lose everything.

00:24.955 --> 00:26.088
(upbeat dramatic music)

00:26.088 --> 00:27.517
- We have two children.

00:27.517 --> 00:29.279
I would like for them not to have to worry

00:29.279 --> 00:31.083
about their mom and dad.

00:31.083 --> 00:34.628
- You've let this business
swallow the both of you up.

00:34.628 --> 00:36.672
I think you deserve something better.

00:36.672 --> 00:38.505
I only hope I'm not too late.

00:38.505 --> 00:40.168
(upbeat music)

00:40.168 --> 00:42.479
(bell dings)

00:42.479 --> 00:44.521
(upbeat rock music)

00:44.521 --> 00:47.302
(spider chirps)

01:03.025 --> 01:04.534
(electricity buzzes)

01:04.534 --> 01:07.452
The Hotel Chester is located
in Starkville, Mississippi,

01:07.452 --> 01:09.642
home to the Mississippi State University.

01:09.642 --> 01:11.999
Husband and wife, David
and Sukie Mollendor,

01:11.999 --> 01:13.823
bought the hotel in 2000.

01:13.823 --> 01:16.149
Before buying the Chester,
David travelled the world

01:16.149 --> 01:17.994
as a hotel trouble-shooter.

01:17.994 --> 01:20.489
- Well, I worked in the
hotel industry 39 years.

01:20.489 --> 01:21.393
(telephone rings)

01:21.393 --> 01:23.260
Thank you for calling Hotel Chester.

01:23.260 --> 01:26.002
Wanted to try and settle
down and give our kids

01:26.002 --> 01:27.726
one stable place to be.

01:29.391 --> 01:32.144
One of us gotta get taller. (laughs)

01:32.144 --> 01:34.240
- [Gordon] To begin
with, a 36-bedroom hotel

01:34.240 --> 01:37.604
was a real success, packed
with students and locals.

01:37.604 --> 01:38.473
- [David] How are you doing?

01:38.473 --> 01:41.278
- [Man] Good, how you doing?
(David laughing)

01:41.278 --> 01:44.399
- [Gordon] Then a sudden
tragedy hit the family.

01:44.399 --> 01:45.791
(siren blaring)

01:45.791 --> 01:46.659
(camera shutters flicker)

01:46.659 --> 01:49.192
(man speaking over radio phone)

01:49.192 --> 01:53.738
- David was coming home and was involved

01:53.738 --> 01:58.472
in a major auto accident.
We thought we'd lost him.

01:58.472 --> 02:01.038
That changed all of us overnight.

02:01.038 --> 02:02.079
(soft music)

02:02.079 --> 02:05.333
- He crushed his feet and was bedridden

02:05.333 --> 02:07.622
for almost six months.

02:07.622 --> 02:10.192
(gentle upbeat music)

02:10.192 --> 02:11.120
- It's a little dated!

02:11.120 --> 02:12.789
- The decor is very dated.

02:12.789 --> 02:15.145
- [Gordon] In David's
absence, standards dropped

02:15.145 --> 02:16.334
and customers stopped coming.

02:16.334 --> 02:18.023
- Well, we were losing so much money

02:18.023 --> 02:20.588
that I had to file for bankruptcy.

02:20.588 --> 02:22.538
- The financial losses have been so bad,

02:22.538 --> 02:24.196
the bank foreclosed on their home,

02:24.196 --> 02:26.083
so now they're living in the hotel.

02:26.083 --> 02:30.066
- Living in the hotel,
working together in the hotel,

02:30.066 --> 02:35.280
I feel tired and I feel
out of sync with the world.

02:36.432 --> 02:37.301
(upbeat dramatic music)

02:37.301 --> 02:38.762
- [Gordon] They couldn't afford payroll,

02:38.762 --> 02:40.796
so Sukie left her job in real estate

02:40.796 --> 02:43.402
and took over as chef
and temporary manager.

02:43.402 --> 02:47.698
- It was my idea that we
open a sushI restaurant.

02:47.698 --> 02:50.441
Never worked in any
restaurant kitchens before

02:50.441 --> 02:55.154
in my entire life, but I
knew how to make the sushi.

02:55.154 --> 02:56.509
- My mouth's confused.

02:56.509 --> 02:58.094
- [Gordon] But despite
her best intentions,

02:58.094 --> 02:59.783
with no formal training-

02:59.783 --> 03:00.652
- Oh!

03:00.652 --> 03:01.521
- [Gordon] She's struggling.

03:01.521 --> 03:06.186
- Oh, uh-uh. Oh, where's my knife!

03:06.186 --> 03:08.115
- [Gordon] Sukie spends
all her time in the hotel,

03:08.115 --> 03:10.888
so she's blind to the tens
of thousands of students

03:10.888 --> 03:13.388
and tourists, who could
be potential customers.

03:13.388 --> 03:15.570
And the hotel's bedrooms and dining room

03:15.570 --> 03:16.875
are empty most nights.

03:16.875 --> 03:18.028
- I just need those entrees.

03:18.028 --> 03:20.106
- [Sukie] Yeah.
- But I guess they're coming.

03:20.106 --> 03:21.618
- You know, I see it if my parent cries,

03:21.618 --> 03:24.412
I see that they're physically exhausted,

03:24.412 --> 03:26.487
that they're mentally drained.

03:26.487 --> 03:29.271
- My mom, she used to be lively, vibrant.

03:29.271 --> 03:32.253
She's honestly half the
woman she used to be.

03:32.253 --> 03:34.328
- Man, I'm losing my mind.

03:34.328 --> 03:38.124
- When I came to this
place I was 180 pounds

03:38.124 --> 03:42.472
of twisted blue steel, sex
appeal and mucho health.

03:42.472 --> 03:47.248
Then this old bitch has worn
me down to 200 pounds of flab,

03:47.248 --> 03:49.173
gab, and (speaks foreign language).

03:54.126 --> 03:55.860
(gentle music)

03:55.860 --> 03:58.175
- [Gordon] With almost no
money coming in to the hotel,

03:58.175 --> 04:01.296
David and Sukie are hanging
on by a very thin thread.

04:02.356 --> 04:05.318
- I need Gordon to help my parents

04:05.318 --> 04:08.394
because if this hotel doesn't change,

04:08.394 --> 04:11.880
it's we lose everything This is it.

04:14.940 --> 04:16.464
(bright upbeat music)

04:16.464 --> 04:17.593
(birds chirping)

04:17.593 --> 04:18.461
(car engine revving)

04:18.461 --> 04:21.365
- I'm in Starkville,
Mississippi's college town.

04:21.365 --> 04:23.190
I'm on my way to the Hotel Chester.

04:24.264 --> 04:28.049
Mississippi State
University, founded in 1878.

04:28.049 --> 04:30.093
Any hotel with a college on their doorstep

04:30.093 --> 04:31.876
should be absolutely thriving,
not just with the students

04:31.876 --> 04:33.909
but with their parents as well.

04:33.909 --> 04:36.307
I can't wait to check-in
to the Hotel Chester.

04:37.537 --> 04:38.706
Where is this place?

04:38.706 --> 04:40.364
(car engine revving)

04:40.364 --> 04:43.252
(gentle upbeat music)

04:43.252 --> 04:44.607
I can't even see the sign.

04:45.637 --> 04:48.895
(soft music) Okay, I'll pull in over here.

04:48.895 --> 04:51.187
They've got to know where it is.

04:51.187 --> 04:52.055
How are you?

04:52.055 --> 04:53.335
- [Male Student] Hey, I'm good.

04:53.335 --> 04:54.846
- I'm looking for the Hotel Chester.

04:54.846 --> 04:55.902
- I've never been there
before. I've passed it.

04:55.902 --> 04:56.770
- You ever been there?

04:56.770 --> 04:57.639
- [Female Student] It's
one block down on the left.

04:57.639 --> 04:59.111
- No, I can't find it, I've
gone 'round three times.

04:59.111 --> 05:00.196
- It's easy to miss.

05:00.196 --> 05:01.124
- [Gordon] Easy to miss?

05:01.124 --> 05:02.588
- Yeah.
- I can't see any signs.

05:02.588 --> 05:03.689
- Well, there may be one sign

05:03.689 --> 05:06.129
but, I mean, it's not too big, no.

05:06.129 --> 05:07.075
- Okay, great.

05:07.075 --> 05:08.287
(girls laughing)

05:08.287 --> 05:11.385
Excellent, thank you, enjoy.

05:11.385 --> 05:13.573
(upbeat dramatic music)

05:13.573 --> 05:15.273
The students never go to the Chester,

05:15.273 --> 05:18.592
despite the fact that it's
right next to the campus, weird!

05:19.809 --> 05:23.910
There we are, there, Historic
Hotel Chester entrance, wow.

05:24.783 --> 05:29.214
Such a huge building and such
a tiny sign, it's madness!

05:29.214 --> 05:30.083
Finally

05:32.196 --> 05:33.448
morning sir! How are you?

05:33.448 --> 05:36.001
- Hey, good morning! How are you?

05:36.001 --> 05:36.870
- Good to see you. Gordon.

05:36.870 --> 05:38.578
- Good to see you and I'm David, Gordon.

05:38.578 --> 05:39.683
- David, nice to see you.

05:39.683 --> 05:42.105
well, I've finally found the place!

05:42.105 --> 05:44.073
That is so confusing there, you know that?

05:44.073 --> 05:46.702
There's no sign on the main
street, I drove straight by!

05:46.702 --> 05:47.571
It was difficult.

05:47.571 --> 05:49.286
- You didn't see 'em on
the corner of the building?

05:49.286 --> 05:51.427
- [Gordon] A tiny sign
saying it's historic?

05:51.427 --> 05:53.043
- That's what's historic about it.

05:53.043 --> 05:53.912
- Oh, that's, that-

05:53.912 --> 05:56.745
- It's historically been a bad entrance.

05:58.389 --> 06:01.350
Now, we have you in an
executive king room.

06:01.350 --> 06:03.999
And then here's two keys for
you 'cause I'm giving you two

06:03.999 --> 06:07.169
because men don't follow
instructions as well as women.

06:07.169 --> 06:10.894
Or in case you get
lucky, hell yes! (laughs)

06:11.924 --> 06:13.008
- So you're a hands-on owner.

06:13.008 --> 06:15.041
Are you running the desk all by yourself?

06:15.041 --> 06:18.712
- My wife is the chef.
She's taught herself.

06:18.712 --> 06:20.244
- Can I meet this lady?

06:20.244 --> 06:22.830
- Well, can I finish my spiel?

06:22.830 --> 06:23.915
- Oh, I thought you'd all ready finished.

06:23.915 --> 06:27.867
- So breakfast is included,
we do have fresh cut fruit.

06:27.867 --> 06:29.264
- That's nice to know, fresh cut fruit.

06:29.264 --> 06:31.488
what would be the alternative, canned?

06:32.475 --> 06:35.384
- No, no fruit, I think
would be the alternative.

06:35.384 --> 06:37.915
- Oh, (laughs) I love
your sense of humour.

06:37.915 --> 06:40.483
(David laughs)
It's dry and very funny.

06:40.483 --> 06:42.225
Fresh cut fruit for breakfast.

06:42.225 --> 06:43.434
- Yes sir.
- Nice.

06:43.434 --> 06:46.394
- Now, I just want you to know
I'm not always at the desk

06:46.394 --> 06:49.075
but you'll be able to recognise me

06:49.075 --> 06:51.161
even if I'm walking away from you

06:51.161 --> 06:53.788
'cause I'm the one who looks
like he's riding a chicken.

06:53.788 --> 06:55.144
- Riding a chicken?
- [David] Yeah.

06:55.144 --> 06:57.094
- I've never ridden a chicken.
you'll have to show me. oh.

06:57.094 --> 06:58.856
- Well, you just have to look at my legs.

06:58.856 --> 06:59.724
- Oh, jeez.

06:59.724 --> 07:03.121
- (laughing) I'll go and get Sukie, okay?

07:03.121 --> 07:07.760
- Okay, great, that poor
chicken. Fucking hell!

07:07.760 --> 07:10.532
(gentle upbeat)

07:10.532 --> 07:11.401
- Ugh! ah!

07:12.810 --> 07:15.667
It's so hot, actually! Ooh!

07:17.041 --> 07:19.230
- I've got a guest that wants to meet you.

07:20.936 --> 07:21.805
- Oh, okay.

07:21.805 --> 07:23.485
- Uh-oh, what do you do with that?

07:23.485 --> 07:25.487
- I am making tamago.

07:25.487 --> 07:29.386
Gordon is here to help
us out and I'm terrified

07:29.386 --> 07:31.889
but at the same time I am so excited.

07:31.889 --> 07:33.443
- Okay, oh!
- [Sukie] Hi!

07:33.443 --> 07:35.455
- Hello, how are you?

07:35.455 --> 07:36.425
Nice to see you.

07:36.425 --> 07:37.843
Don't worry, I've had
worse than wet hands,

07:37.843 --> 07:38.711
nice to meet you.

07:38.711 --> 07:39.580
- I washed my hands.

07:39.580 --> 07:41.446
- That was very kind, thank
you for that. (lips smacking)

07:41.446 --> 07:42.816
- Thank you.
- Sukie, right?

07:42.816 --> 07:43.685
- Nice to meet you.

07:43.685 --> 07:45.422
- Likewise, good to see
you too. (David laughs)

07:45.422 --> 07:46.935
What's it like working with your wife?

07:46.935 --> 07:49.938
- I love my wife so it's
nice to be around her

07:49.938 --> 07:53.139
until she gets her nose out of joint.

07:53.139 --> 07:54.849
She has a chef's temperament.

07:54.849 --> 07:56.799
If you're not familiar with it,

07:56.799 --> 07:59.197
well, they can fly off
the handle pretty easy.

08:00.543 --> 08:01.523
- What's your background?

08:01.523 --> 08:02.680
- I'm a hotel guy.

08:02.680 --> 08:05.124
I was in Vietnam and I
went to hotel school.

08:05.124 --> 08:06.700
- So you've owned other hotels?

08:06.700 --> 08:08.478
So you've qualified as a hotelier?

08:08.478 --> 08:11.001
- Well, so in my view, yeah. (laughs)

08:11.001 --> 08:13.639
- Well, that's very good!
That's good to hear!

08:13.639 --> 08:18.581
- Graduated with a major in
hotel and restaurant management

08:18.581 --> 08:21.126
and have been in the
business almost 40 years.

08:21.126 --> 08:23.347
- [Gordon] So, in a nutshell,
what's wrong with the hotel?

08:23.347 --> 08:25.182
- That's the question, we're not sure.

08:25.182 --> 08:27.135
we don't think it's a quality issue,

08:28.164 --> 08:32.085
neither for our rooms or
our food and beverage.

08:32.085 --> 08:33.440
- Why don't you both show me to the room?

08:33.440 --> 08:34.482
- [Sukie] Okay.

08:34.482 --> 08:37.423
- I've been a general
manager of a lot of hotels.

08:37.423 --> 08:40.113
I eventually became a turnaround guy

08:40.113 --> 08:42.313
to take on problem properties.

08:42.313 --> 08:46.213
So my big surprise here is that
I'm having a hell of a time

08:46.213 --> 08:48.445
trying to turn this thing around.

08:48.445 --> 08:49.695
We just call it an executive king.

08:49.695 --> 08:50.563
- Oh, wow.

08:51.510 --> 08:54.816
Oh, dear, okay, this is it? Yes sir.

08:54.816 --> 08:55.872
What is that, suede?

08:56.870 --> 08:59.602
- It's leather, but it's a rough leather

08:59.602 --> 09:01.336
and very difficult to clean.

09:02.605 --> 09:05.472
- And it's so bland! I mean,
it's like a cheap motel chain.

09:05.472 --> 09:08.141
I feel like I'm in the
witness protection programme!

09:08.141 --> 09:09.163
It's depressing here!

09:09.163 --> 09:11.150
So when was the last time
the rooms were touched?

09:11.150 --> 09:12.257
- 2003.

09:12.257 --> 09:14.319
- 2003, so ten years ago.
- Yeah.

09:14.319 --> 09:16.407
- It feels like something
out of the 1970s.

09:16.407 --> 09:18.670
- Our hotel rooms are dated.

09:18.670 --> 09:21.883
You know, we try to call
it period furniture.

09:21.883 --> 09:23.177
- Yeah, I don't know what to say,

09:23.177 --> 09:26.013
always tells you that
a place on the decline

09:26.013 --> 09:28.860
when you walk in and you've
got walls that are a mess,

09:28.860 --> 09:31.488
scuffs everywhere and
big marks on the sofas

09:31.488 --> 09:33.886
that you're expected to pay
good money to sit down in.

09:33.886 --> 09:36.319
So far, I'm not digging it.

09:37.603 --> 09:39.610
I'm gonna unpack and then
I'd like to come down

09:39.610 --> 09:41.258
and have a bite to eat.

09:41.258 --> 09:43.114
Sukie, so what's your
experience in the kitchen?

09:43.114 --> 09:46.229
- My father had a sushI
restaurant in Washington, D.C.

09:46.229 --> 09:47.098
- Parents have a Japanese restaurant?

09:47.098 --> 09:48.429
- Yeah, had, my father passed away.

09:48.429 --> 09:49.646
- And did you grow up in the kitchen?

09:49.646 --> 09:50.621
- Of course!

09:50.621 --> 09:52.102
- But did you work in the kitchen?

09:52.102 --> 09:53.208
- No, just washing dishes.

09:53.208 --> 09:54.077
(upbeat dramatic music)

09:54.077 --> 09:58.158
(David and Sukie laughing)

09:58.158 --> 10:00.673
- Anyway, listen, I'm gonna
unpack. Thank you, yeah?

10:00.673 --> 10:01.542
- Okay, hey, thank you.
Yes sir, nice meeting you.

10:01.542 --> 10:02.410
- Good to see you.

10:02.410 --> 10:04.140
Likewise, and I'll pop
down and have a bit to eat.

10:04.140 --> 10:06.228
- Okay. All right.
- Okay? Thank you.

10:08.099 --> 10:12.007
- So I feel like the guy
who walked into a bar

10:12.007 --> 10:15.261
with a big frog on his
head, went up to the bar

